#### Issue description
I wanted to port my code that uses pybind11 on Linux to also run on Windows. However, I kept getting a C1001. I boiled it down to the use of `overload_cast`


#### Reproducible example code
I used the 64bit cmake VS generator

```cpp
#include "pybind11/pybind11.h"

struct Pet {
    Pet(const std::string &name, int age) : name(name), age(age) { }

    void set(int age_) { age = age_; }
    void set(const std::string &name_) { name = name_; }

    std::string name;
    int age;
};


PYBIND11_PLUGIN(pytest)
{
	namespace py = pybind11;
	py::module m(
        "pytest", 
        "Module description goes here.");

	py::class_<Pet>(m, "Pet")
		.def("set", py::overload_cast<int>(&Pet::set), "Set the pet's age")
		.def("set", py::overload_cast<const std::string &>(&Pet::set), "Set the pet's name");

    return m.ptr();
} 
```

```cmake
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.6)
project(test_pybind11 CXX)
add_subdirectory(pybind11)
pybind11_add_module(pytest MODULE main.cpp)
```

